{{Infobox River | name = Tagawa | image = [[File:Tagawa in 2005-06.jpg|300px]] | image_caption = View from Sai Bridge (Utsunomiya City) | river_system_class = [[First-class water system]] | river_system = [[Tone River]] | type = First-class river | length = 77.9 km | source_elevation = 550 m | flow = 10 m³/s | observation_station = | basin_size = 245.8 km² | source = {{ill|Nikkō|ja|日光市}} Shichiri | mouth = [[Kinugawa River]] ({{ill|Oyama|ja|小山市}}, Tochigi Prefecture) | basin_countries = [[Tochigi Prefecture]] | notes = | references = }}
'''Tagawa''' (田川) is a [[first-class river]] in Japan that originates in {{ill|Nikkō|ja|日光市}}, flows through {{ill|Utsunomiya|ja|宇都宮市}}, {{ill|Shimotsuke|ja|下野市}}, and merges with the [[Kinugawa River]] via the '''Tagawa Diversion Channel''' in {{ill|Oyama|ja|小山市}}, Tochigi Prefecture. While the old course extended into {{ill|Yūki|ja|結城市}} in Ibaraki Prefecture, the practical river mouth is now in Oyama due to the channel's construction.
== Geography == The Tagawa originates in the low mountains of Shichiri in Nikkō and the watershed of {{ill|Shidobuchi River|ja|志度淵川}}. It passes through areas like Nikkō's Inokura, Utsunomiya's Ishinata and Tokujirō towns, and Utsunomiya City Center, eventually flowing through Kawada, Yokota, {{ill|Kaminokawa|ja|上三川町}} Ishida, {{ill|Shimotsuke|ja|下野市}} Yachiga, and {{ill|Oyama|ja|小山市}} Enjimashinden before joining the Kinugawa River via the diversion channel.
The river's total length is 78 km, and its basin area covers 245.8 km², making it the largest tributary of the Kinugawa River. Tagawa's tributaries include 11 first-class rivers such as {{ill|Akaborigawa|ja|赤堀川 (栃木県)}} and {{ill|Yamadagawa|ja|山田川 (栃木県)}}.
The upper reaches of Tagawa flow through serene rural landscapes, including orchards and wooded areas. The mid-to-lower reaches run through Utsunomiya's urban areas and serve as irrigation for rice paddies.
Since the early Edo period, water from the Tagawa was utilized for irrigation, helping to cultivate rice fields in the surrounding regions. However, the river was also notorious as a "raging river," frequently changing its course due to flooding. Flood control measures like canals and levees have been implemented over the years.
== History == Historically, the Tagawa was known as a "raging river," frequently altering its course due to heavy rain and flooding. Fertile soil was deposited in the floodplains, while the upper and middle reaches developed river terraces along the valley, forming alluvial plains.
During the Edo period, the river's water was diverted for irrigation by the {{ill|Utsunomiya Domain|ja|宇都宮藩}} and the {{ill|Tokugawa Shogunate|ja|江戸幕府}}. Notable irrigation works include {{ill|Takaragi Canal (Shinkawa)|ja|宝木用水（新川）}}, constructed by {{ill|Ninomiya Sontoku|ja|二宮尊徳}} to supply water to the northwest plateau of Utsunomiya, and the Yoshida Canal, which served downstream areas in Shimotsuke, Oyama, and Yūki.
== Flood Control == Flood control measures for the Tagawa date back to historical times, including levees to prevent overflow. In modern times, typhoon and rainfall-induced flood prevention projects have been undertaken. Construction along the river's mid-to-lower reaches, including diversion channels and channel renovations, is ongoing. Urbanization in the basin has increased the volume of rainwater entering the river during heavy rainfall, necessitating enhanced flood mitigation downstream.
Key flood events include: - **1947 (Shōwa 22)**: Flooding from the {{ill|Typhoon Kathleen|ja|カスリーン台風}} caused extensive damage, with 300+ fatalities, 40,000 flooded homes, and 25,000 ha of inundated farmland in Tochigi Prefecture. - **1986 (Shōwa 61)**: Typhoon 10 caused significant flooding, inundating 46 ha and 200+ houses. - **1997 (Heisei 9)**: Typhoon 7 led to 35 ha of flood damage. - **1998 (Heisei 10)**: Heavy rain caused 81 ha of flood damage. - **2019 (Reiwa 1)**: {{ill|Typhoon Hagibis|ja|令和元年東日本台風}} caused widespread flooding. Water levels exceeded the danger threshold for 9 hours, and significant inundation occurred in western Utsunomiya.<ref name="bousai">{{Cite web|url=https://www.zenkokubousai.or.jp/monthly/image/no857high.pdf|author=Tochigi Prefecture River Section|title=Reiwa Year 1 Disaster in Tochigi Prefecture|publisher=National Disaster Association|access-date=2022-09-19}}</ref>
